# React Native Styling

## NativeWind `className` Does NOT Work on Gluestack Components

Gluestack UI components (`Text`, `Box`, `Button`, etc. from `@gluestack-ui/themed`) have their own styling system. NativeWind's `className` prop is **silently ignored** on them — styles won't apply with no error.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — className is silently ignored on Gluestack Text
import { Text } from '@gluestack-ui/themed';
<Text className="text-headline-md text-primary">Hello</Text>  // renders unstyled

// ✅ GOOD — use RN Text + inline style
import { Text } from 'react-native';
<Text style={{ fontSize: 20, fontWeight: '600', color: '#4CAF50' }}>Hello</Text>

// ✅ GOOD — use RN Text + NativeWind className
import { Text } from 'react-native';
<Text className="text-headline-md text-primary">Hello</Text>

// ✅ GOOD — use Gluestack props (no className)
import { Text } from '@gluestack-ui/themed';
<Text size="lg" bold>Hello</Text>
```

## Decision Matrix

| Component Source | className works? | Use for |
|---|---|---|
| `react-native` (`View`, `Text`, `Pressable`) | ✅ Yes | Layout, text, simple UIs |
| `react-native-reanimated` (`Animated.View`) | ✅ Yes | Animated containers |
| `@gluestack-ui/themed` (`Text`, `Box`, etc.) | ❌ No | Only when using Gluestack semantic props |

## Recommendation

For screens and feature components, prefer **React Native primitives + inline `style` objects** using design tokens from `~/shared/theme/tokens.ts`. This avoids all NativeWind/Gluestack interop issues and is guaranteed to render correctly.

```tsx
import { View, Text } from 'react-native';
import { colors, spacing } from '~/shared/theme/tokens';

<View style={{ padding: spacing.md, backgroundColor: colors.surface.card }}>
  <Text style={{ fontSize: 20, fontWeight: '600', color: colors.text.primary }}>
    Title
  </Text>
</View>
```
